539
58:07.680 --> 58:15.942
This time as we do the simplification, we'll need to pull out a factor of omega R to see that indeed we have an eogenvector

540
58:15.942 --> 58:22.650
and that vector of omega R represents the eigenvalue associated with this eigenvector.

541
58:22.650 --> 58:29.100
So that's a second eigenvector
eigenvalue pair of NA.

542
58:29.100 --> 58:37.170
We can identify additional eigenvectors using exactly the same reasoning, And in fact, if we simply replace omega R

543
58:37.170 --> 58:44.580
with omega R to the power J for each J between zero and R minus one, we'll always get an eigenvector,

544
58:44.580 --> 58:49.260
and the associated eigenvalue will be omega R to the power J.

545
58:49.260 --> 58:57.960
So this actually includes
psi zero and pis one, which we already saw
as well as R minus two, other eigenvector, eigenvalue pairs.

546
58:57.960 --> 59:04.680
They all work in basically the same way, and to verify them, we just need to know that A to the power R equals one

547
59:04.680 --> 59:09.180
as well as omega R to
the power R equals one.

548
59:09.180 --> 59:17.441
There are other eigenvectors of MA like cat zero for instance, but they aren't going to be useful to us and we don't need to worry about them.

549
59:17.441 --> 59:20.820
We only need to worry about psi zero through psi R minus one.

550
59:20.820 --> 59:26.820
Let's focus on psi one for a moment, just to try to understand why it is that we care about these eigenvectors

551
59:26.820 --> 59:33.960
and what they can tell
us about the order R, which is what we're trying to find.

552
59:33.960 --> 59:43.110
Supposing that we're given
the eigenvector psi one, we can attempt to learn
R in the following way.

553
59:43.110 --> 59:52.560
First, we perform phase
estimation on this eigenvector using a quantum circuit that
implements the operation MA.

554
59:52.560 --> 59:58.980
What we get is an approximation to theta, which is one over R in this case.

555
59:58.980 --> 60:06.600
And second because we're looking for R and we have an
approximation to one over R, the natural thing to do is
to compute the reciprocal

556
60:06.600 --> 60:13.350
and to round it off to
the nearest integer. We have to round like this
because R has to be an integer.

557
60:13.350 --> 60:18.360
But we don't have one of our R exactly, we just have an approximation to it.

558
60:18.360 --> 60:26.189
But if the approximation is good enough, we'll get R when we round,
which is what we're looking for.

559
60:26.189 --> 60:34.590
And now the question is how much precision do we need to correctly determine R by computing the reciprocal and rounding?

560
60:34.590 --> 60:42.330
Or in other words, how accurate does our
approximation need to be to make this all work?

561
60:42.330 --> 60:47.130
Well, it turns out that we do need a pretty accurate approximation.

562
60:47.130 --> 60:54.540
For example, we can't
afford to confuse one over R with one over R plus one, or one over R minus one for instance.

563
60:54.540 --> 61:01.980
In those two fractions, one over R plus one and
one over R minus one are pretty close to one
over R when R is large.

564
61:01.980 --> 61:10.710
But although we do need a
pretty accurate approximation, we don't need a ridiculously
accurate approximation, and it can be shown that
if our approximation

565
61:10.710 --> 61:18.570
satisfies the inequality that
we have here on the screen, then rounding off will
give us the right answer.

566
61:18.570 --> 61:27.510
I won't try to argue that in this video, but it is shown in the written
material for the lesson in case you're interested in the details.

567
61:27.510 --> 61:35.310
And if that's the accuracy
that we're going for, then it suffices to use a
number of control qubits in the phase estimation procedure

568
61:35.310 --> 61:38.970
that's equal to two times
the length of N plus one.

569
61:38.970 --> 61:46.230
Where as we had in the previous lessons, the length of N is the number of bits that we need to express N in binary.

570
61:46.230 --> 61:52.980
By the way, if we're content
to get the best approximation with probability at least 40% and we don't try to
increase our confidence

571
61:52.980 --> 61:56.790
like I described earlier, then we don't actually need the plus one.

572
61:56.790 --> 62:05.370
But in any case, we have that the number
of control qubits we need is linear in the length of N
written as a binary string.

573
62:05.370 --> 62:14.130
We've seen that if we have
the eigenvector psi one, we can use phase estimation to find R, provided we use enough accuracy.

574
62:14.130 --> 62:18.330
Unfortunately it's not so easy to get our hands on this eigenvector.

575
62:18.330 --> 62:22.020
So let's ask a different question.

576
62:22.020 --> 62:28.680
Suppose we don't have psi one, but rather we have psi
for a random choice of J.

577
62:28.680 --> 62:35.250
Can we still figure out what R is? Or at the very least can we
figure out something about R?

578
62:35.250 --> 62:42.150
And the answer is yes, we can figure out something
about R, at least on average.

579
62:42.150 --> 62:48.540
What we can do is to try
to figure out J over R using a very similar method
to the one that we just saw,

580
62:48.540 --> 62:51.780
but with a key difference.

581
62:51.780 --> 62:59.100
First, we'll do exactly the
same thing we did before, which is to run the phase
estimation procedure on the eigenvector psi J.

582
62:59.100 --> 63:06.600
And what we'll get is an
approximation to J over R, as opposed to one over R,
which is what we had before.

583
63:06.600 --> 63:13.950
But now we have a small problem, because computing the
reciprocal won't give us R, it will give us R over J.

584
63:13.950 --> 63:20.490
And by the way, we're not
assuming that we know what J is, we're simply given psi J for a random J,

585
63:20.490 --> 63:26.580
and we're not told what J is. So what can we do?

586
63:26.580 --> 63:34.380
Well, it turns out that there's a well-known
classical algorithm that can help us, called the
continued fraction algorithm.

587
63:34.380 --> 63:41.790
And what this algorithm can do is to take our approximation
Y over two to the M and tell us which fraction U over V,

588
63:41.790 --> 63:50.880
written in lowest terms, and where U and V are both
integers smaller than N is closest to our approximation.

